### **Install Multi System Reporting**
**The MSR installer package contains the following files/zip:**
- **msr** - shell script to precheck, install, update, uninstall and validate the multi system reporting solution.
- **config.properties** - configuration file for the multi system reporting solution installation and management.
- **msr.tar.gz** - contains all the binaries needed for 'msr' shell script execution.
- **README.md** - instructions on how to manually install the prerequisites needed for the multi system reporting solution.
- **build.info** - build version details for the multi system reporting solution.

- Update required PostgreSQL & Grafana password in config.properties file before installation. Skip for default.
- Update other required configurations in config.properties file before installation. Skip for defaults.

#### MSR Installation Commands:
```bash
# To get help on MSR installer
bash msr --help

# To run precheck for MSR installation
bash msr --precheck

# To run precheck for MSR installation
bash msr --version

# To start MSR installation (default option to install all i.e. with prerequisites)
bash msr --install

# To list options & run individual installation
bash msr --install --help
bash msr --install <option>

# To validate the status of services after MSR installation
bash msr --validate

# To list options & update MSR components
bash msr --update --help
bash msr --update <option>

# To list options & uninstall MSR components
bash msr --uninstall --help
bash msr --uninstall <option>
```

#### MSR Split Installation Commands:
- PostgreSQL and Grafana can be on same or different hosts as required.
- Update required PostgreSQL & Grafana password in config.properties file before installation. Skip for default.
- MSR can be on installed on a different host.
- Before installing MSR, update PostgreSQL configuration in config.properties file of MSR host.
- Before installing Grafana dashboards, update PostgreSQL configuration in config.properties file of Grafana host.
- Use below commands as per requirement:
```bash
# To install Grafana
bash msr --install grafana

# To install PostgreSQL
bash msr --install postgres

# To install MSR (data-collector) it requires java and otel installation
bash msr --install java
bash msr --install otel
bash msr --install dcs

# To install Grafana dashboards (Login to host where Grafana is installed)
bash msr --install grafana-dashboards
```

#### MSR Scaling the Data Collector:
- The MSR (data collector) can be scaled, as your data increases.
- Data collector can be installed as **CENTRAL** or **EDGE** mode.
- **CENTRAL** mode Data collector has data collector as well as data exporter, which exports data to timescale database.
- EDGE mode has only Data collector, and the data collected at various edge data collectors is forwarded to CENTRAL node.
- Default Data Collector installation is **CENTRAL** mode. There can be only one **CENTRAL** mode Data Collector.

To install MSR in **EDGE** mode,
- Update the config.properties file for below properties 
  - DCS_CONFIG_MODE='EDGE'
  - DCS_CENTRAL_NODE_HOST=&lt;ip-of-central-node-data-collector&gt;
  - Use below commands for installation:
```bash
# To install MSR (data-collector) it requires java and otel installation
bash msr --install java
bash msr --install otel
bash msr --install dcs
```

#### MSR Update Commands:
- Download and extract the MSR latest package. 
- MSR provides the below commands to update the MSR components.
```bash
# To update the MSR (data-collector), database schema and required binaries
bash msr --update dcs

# To overwrite the existing Grafana dashboards & add any new ones
bash msr --update grafana-dashboards
```

#### MSR Configuration Commands:
The below commands can be used to manage systems for data collection:
```bash
# Add a single system to the data collector
dpsmsm system add --host <FQDN/IP> --username <username> --password <password>
dpsmsm system add --type <type>- --host <FQDN/IP> --clientid <clientid> --secretkey <secretkey>

# Add multiple systems using a JSON configuration file
dpsmsm system batch-add --file <JSON file path>

# Show systems
dpsmsm system show --all 
dpsmsm system show --host <FQDN/IP>  

# Enable data collection for a system (using either ID or host)
dpsmsm system enable --id <system ID>
dpsmsm system enable --host <FQDN/IP>

# Disable data collection for a system (using either ID or host)
dpsmsm system disable --id <system ID>
dpsmsm system disable --host <FQDN/IP>

# Retire a system while retaining collected data (using either ID or host)
dpsmsm system retire --id <system ID>
dpsmsm system retire --host <FQDN/IP>

# Delete a system and its collected data (using either ID or host)
dpsmsm system delete --id <system ID>
dpsmsm system delete --host <FQDN/IP>

# Modify system settings
dpsmsm system modify --id <system ID> --host <FQDN/IP> --username <username> --password <password>
dpsmsm system modify --id <system ID> --host <FQDN/IP> --clientid <clientid> --secretkey <secretkey>

# Initiate data collection
dpsmsm system collect --all                
dpsmsm system collect --host <FQDN/IP> 
```

### Manual Installation Help for Prerequisites
#### Install Java17:
- Login as root user and enable repositories (if needed).
- Turn off the firewall: **systemctl stop firewalld**
- To install openjdk17 on SLES 15.4 SP4 run: **zypper install java-17-openjdk-headless**
- To install openjdk17 on CentOS 9 run: **dnf install java-17-openjdk-headless**
- To validate version for java installed run: **java -version**

#### OpenTelemetry Collector Installation:
- Login as root user and enable repositories (if needed).
- Turn off the firewall: **systemctl stop firewalld**
- Get OpenTelemetry Collector 0.144.0 RPM using: **wget https://github.com/open-telemetry/opentelemetry-collector-releases/releases/download/v0.144.0/otelcol-contrib_0.144.0_linux_amd64.rpm**
- Install OpenTelemetry Collector RPM using: **rpm -ivh otelcol-contrib_0.144.0_linux_amd64.rpm**
- To validate version for OpenTelemetry Collector installed run: **otelcol-contrib --version**

#### Grafana Server Installation & Configuration:
- Login as root user and enable repositories (if needed).
- Turn off the firewall: **systemctl stop firewalld**
- Install grafana referring to below:
   - Get Grafana rpm using: **wget https://dl.grafana.com/grafana-enterprise/release/12.4.2/grafana-enterprise_12.4.2_23531306697_linux_amd64.rpm**
   - Install Grafana rpm using: **grafana-enterprise_12.4.2_23531306697_linux_amd64.rpm**
- Edit config at /etc/grafana/grafana.ini and edit following entry:
   1. ```;http_port = 3000 ``` remove ";" and update the default **3000** port if needed, else skip.
   2. ```;protocol = http ``` remove ";" and update **http** to **https**.
   3. ```;login_maximum_inactive_lifetime_duration =``` remove ";" and update as **login_maximum_inactive_lifetime_duration = 2M**
   4. ```;login_maximum_lifetime_duration =``` remove ";" and update as **login_maximum_lifetime_duration = 2M**
   5. ```;token_rotation_interval_minutes = 10``` remove ";" and update as **token_rotation_interval_minutes = 1000**
- Restart Grafana via command: **systemctl restart grafana-server**
- To validate if grafana server is up & running use: **systemctl is-active grafana-server**
- Login to a browser and access URL: **https://<grafana_server_ip>:<port>/**

#### PostgreSQL (with TimescaleDB) Installation & Configuration (SLES/openSUSE) :
- Login as root user and enable repositories (if needed).
- Turn off the firewall: **systemctl stop firewalld**
- Install PostgreSQL:
   - run: **zypper install postgresql16-server postgresql16-server-devel**
   - validate the installation using: psql --version
- Create a directory for PostgreSQL installation: **mkdir -p &lt;path&gt;**
- Add ownership for database user to installation directory: **chown -R postgres:postgres &lt;path&gt;**
- Update **/etc/sysconfig/postgresql** environment file to update **POSTGRES_DATADIR="&lt;path&gt;"** and save file.
- Configure PostgreSQL using below commands:
   - Switch to postgres user using: **su - postgres**
   - Initialize PostgreSQL database using: **initdb --pgdata &lt;path&gt;**
   - Exit from postgres user using: **exit** or **\q**
   - Start PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl start postgresql.service**
   - Connect to PostgreSQL command line using: **psql -U postgres -h 127.0.0.1**
   - Alter password for postgres user using: **alter user postgres password 'Password123!';**
     If the password change was successful, you will see **ALTER ROLE** in output.
   - Exit from postgres user using: **\q**
- Update PostgreSQL using below commands:
- Stop PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl stop postgresql.service**
- Update the **&lt;path&gt;/data/pg_hba.conf** file, and add below under the IPv4 section:
  ```host all all 0.0.0.0/0 scram-sha-256```
- Update the **&lt;path&gt;/data/postgresql.conf** file, alter the below configurations:
  ```listen_addresses = '*'```
  ```port = 5432```
  ```max_locks_per_transaction = 2048```
- Install git-core, cmake and gcc using: **zypper install git-core gcc cmake**
- Follow **https://docs.timescale.com/self-hosted/latest/install/installation-source/** to install timescaledb extension from source, use version 2.16.1
-  Update **&lt;path&gt;/data/postgresql.conf** file, and alter below config:
   ```shared_preload_libraries = 'timescaledb'```
- Start PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl start postgresql.service**
- Connect to PostgreSQL using: **psql -U postgres -h 127.0.0.1 -p 5432** and authenticate using the password set above.
- In order to enable the timescaledb extension run: **CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS timescaledb;**
- To validate the timescaledb extension added, run: **\dx**.

#### PostgreSQL (with TimescaleDB) Installation & Configuration (CentOS/RHEL):
- Login as root user and enable repositories (if needed).
- Turn off the firewall: **systemctl stop firewalld**
- Install PostgreSQL:
   - run: **dnf module install postgresql:16**
   - run: **dnf install postgresql-server-devel**
   - validate the installation using: psql --version
- Create a directory for PostgreSQL installation: **mkdir -p &lt;path&gt;**
- Add ownership for database user to installation directory: **chown -R postgres:postgres &lt;path&gt;**
- Update **/usr/lib/systemd/system/postgresql.service** file to update **Environment=PGDATA=&lt;path&gt;** and save file.
- Configure PostgreSQL using below commands:
   - Switch to postgres user using: **su - postgres**
   - Initialize PostgreSQL database using: **initdb --pgdata &lt;path&gt;**
   - Exit from postgres user using: **exit** or **\q**
   - Set required permissions on &lt;path&gt; using: **chcon -Rt postgresql_db_t &lt;path&gt;**
   - Enable PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl enable postgresql.service**
   - Start PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl start postgresql.service**
   - Connect to PostgreSQL command line using: **psql -U postgres -h 127.0.0.1**
   - Alter password for postgres user using: **alter user postgres password 'Password123!';**
     If the password change was successful, you will see **ALTER ROLE** in output.
   - Exit from postgres user using: **\q**
- Update PostgreSQL using below commands:
   - Stop PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl stop postgresql.service**
   - Update the &lt;path&gt;/data/pg_hba.conf file, and add below under the IPv4 section:
     ```host all all 0.0.0.0/0 scram-sha-256```
   - Update the &lt;path&gt;/data/postgresql.conf file, alter the below configs:
     ```listen_addresses = '*'```
     ```port = 5432```
     ```max_locks_per_transaction = 2048```
- Install git-core, cmake, gcc, rpm-build & openssl-devel using: **dnf install git-core gcc cmake rpm-build openssl-devel**
- Follow **https://docs.timescale.com/self-hosted/latest/install/installation-source/** to install timescaledb extension from source, use version 2.16.1
-  Update **&lt;path&gt;/data/postgresql.conf** file, and alter below config:
   ```shared_preload_libraries = 'timescaledb'```
- Start PostgreSQL service using: **systemctl start postgresql.service**
- Connect to PostgreSQL using: **psql -U postgres -h 127.0.0.1 -p 5432** and authenticate using the password set above.
- In order to enable the timescaledb extension run: **CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS timescaledb;**
- To validate the timescaledb extension added, run: **\dx**.

### Notes:
1. The firewall rules must be set to allow grafana and postgresql connections.
2. The system's hostname must match the system FQDN (part) for the lockbox operations.
3. The recommended size for PostgreSQL data directory (defined as POSTGRES_DATA_DIR in config.properties) is 500G.
4. **Default Grafana Credentials**:
   ```Host: <system-ip-or-hostname>, Post: 3000, Protocol: https, User: admin, & Password: Password123!```
5. **Default PostgreSQL Credentials**:
   ```Host: <system-ip-or-hostname>, Port: 5432, User: postgres & Password: Password123!```















